article:
A 'transposition' in chess is a sequence of moves that results in a position
which may also be reached by another, more common sequence of moves.
Transpositions are particularly common in opening, where a given position may
be reached by different sequences of moves. Players sometimes use
transpositions deliberately in order to avoid variations they dislike, lure
opponents into unfamiliar or uncomfortable territory or simply to worry
opponents. See review at 

In chess the verb "'transpose'" means shifting the game on to a different
opening track from that on which it started.

Transposition tables are an essential part of a computer chess program.
